Certainly! Below is a simple HTML web app example with embedded CSS and JavaScript all contained within a single HTML file. This example creates a basic to-do list application where users can add and remove tasks. You can copy this code into an HTML file and open it in a web browser to see it in action.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Simple To-Do List</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 20px;
        }
        h1 {
            text-align: center;
        }
        #taskInput {
            padding: 10px;
            width: 200px;
        }
        #addTask {
            padding: 10px;
            cursor: pointer;
            background-color: #28a745;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
        #taskList {
            margin-top: 20px;
            list-style-type: none;
            padding: 0;
        }
        .task {
            background: #fff;
            padding: 10px;
            margin: 5px 0;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: space-between;
            align-items: center;
            border-radius: 5px;
            box-shadow: 0 2px 5px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
        }
        .removeTask {
            cursor: pointer;
            color: #dc3545;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <h1>To-Do List</h1>

    <input type="text" id="taskInput" placeholder="Add a new task">
    <button id="addTask">Add Task</button>

    <ul id="taskList"></ul>

    <script>
        const addTaskButton = document.getElementById('addTask');
        const taskInput = document.getElementById('taskInput');
        const taskList = document.getElementById('taskList');

        addTaskButton.addEventListener('click', function() {
            const taskText = taskInput.value;
            if (taskText === '') return;

            const li = document.createElement('li');
            li.className = 'task';

            li.innerHTML = `
                ${taskText} 
                <span class="removeTask">‚ùå</span>
            `;

            taskList.appendChild(li);
            taskInput.value = '';

            const removeTaskButton = li.querySelector('.removeTask');
            removeTaskButton.addEventListener('click', function() {
                taskList.removeChild(li);
            });
        });
    </script>

</body>
</html>
```

### How to Use:
1. Copy the above code.
2. Paste it into a plain text editor (like Notepad on Windows, TextEdit on Mac, or any code editor).
3. Save the file with a `.html` extension, for example, `todo.html`.
4. Open the saved file in a web browser (like Chrome, Firefox, etc.).

You will see a simple To-Do List app where you can add tasks and remove them by clicking the delete button (marked with a red cross).
